If you reside in Fort Greene, you’ve undoubtedly heard of LaRina, which makes a strong claim for the title of best restaurant in the neighborhood. If you’re an outsider, be prepared for outstanding Italian experience. LaRina has built a reputation that everything on their menu is a worthy consideration, you’ll be taken aback with the very intentional care with each unique offering. The dishes are prepared with precision, attention to detail, and thoughtfulness; the proof is in each delicious bite. In regards to antipasti, the burrata is a rich, creamy and delectable starter. All of their pastas are made to please however they’ve received a lot of attention over their smoked Spaghetti Aglio E Olio which tastes like your eating this dish fresh off a smoker. Unreal. The lasagna, is expertly constructed and the dance between the bolognese and the béchamel offers a satisfying array of flavors in your mouth. The lasagna is great option for those seeking an entree on the heavier side as many of their pasta dishes are modestly portioned. For desert, I recommend the salted caramel Panna Cotta, the cool creamy finale is a refreshing way to end your LaRina rendezvous. One trip to LaRina and you’ll quickly realize why there has been so much positive buzz in the neighborhood regarding their dining experience. Perfect option for date night or for a meal that will be extremely satisfying without blowing a hole in your wallet.

Authentic Italian spot in Williamsburg, owned by a team of Italian chefs and restauranteurs. Very reliable food (I'm Italian) and warm ambiance, indoor and outdoor in the garden. Definitely don't miss it if you're around.

Wow!  My family and I went to LaRina for dinner because Silvia’s food looked so great on Top Chef. We expected a good meal; what we didn’t expect was to have the greatest pasta of our lives!  I rarely order spaghetti because it’s typically forgettable, but Silvia’s smoked spaghetti was sublime: an explosion of flavor in every bite!  The scallop crudo was amazing, too. And could panna cotta get any better?...I don’t think so. The cocktails were also outstanding. We will now crave this food and look forward to returning frequently to LaRina.

My husband has been wanting to come here for a while since it's a top chef restaurant (yay Silvia!), and we finally made it for our mini 5.5yr anniversary date. Cute little spot, but tables are a bit cramped. Here's what we tried:  BURRATA $17 (basil pesto - ramps - pistacchio - grilled bread) This was VERYYYY good! The burrata was sooo soft, loved the consistency. The pesto and pistacchio were perfect complements to the burrata, super flavorful.  SPAGHETTI AGLIO E OLIO $19 (smoked spaghetti - garlic - olive oil - calabrian chili - hazelnuts) I was really excited for this item, but unfortunately it tasted just a bit undercooked. You could tell when you chewed on it and the fact that the noodles looked kinda broken in the bowl. I could see how this could be a standout dish, but it didn't deliver today. Pretty simple, no meats, really just garlic/olive oil.  MEZZELUNE $24 (blue crab - saffron bisque - chives) This one was really interesting, the bisque was nice and tangy which helped make the dish a lot lighter. There could have been more crab flavor, but there was a good amount in each pasta pillow haha.  PAPPARDELLE DI SEGALE $23 (beef short ribs - green peas - mint) yummmm probably my favorite. The pappardelle was perfectly cooked and seasoned. I wish the short ribs were more seasoned though, if you ate it on its own, you'd probably find it extremely light compared to the pappardelle.  Closer to a 3.5 star review, but not bad. On my next visit, I'd like to try the Lasagne Verdi. I've also heard great things about the artichoke app but it's no longer on the menu (bring it back!) ;(.  *FYI - do NOT go on a hot day...they do not have AC that is strong enough, it really felt mostly like the ceiling fans, which is completely not enough. They have a really cute outdoor seating area, so yeah...wait until it's cool out!

The experience at this restaurant was so terrible that it stuck with me for days.  I had eaten lunch here once with my mother and we really enjoyed it and had good service.  Came back for my mother's 65th birthday with my family and we ordered two appetizers: the mission fig salad and fried zucchini flowers.  The fried food came out cold but, we let it slide.  We ordered everything at the same time and my brother's cold entree came out first (20 minutes after the appetizers) then my boyfriend's lasagna came 10 minutes later, then 20 minutes later my parents food came, and then 10 minutes later my pasta dish came.  So at no point did we actually get to eat together.  The waitress was pleasant but, did not tell us what went wrong and didn't inform us on the long wait.  Other tables were seated 20 minutes after us and were served before us.  I went in to try to talk to someone about how we were waiting to get the rest of our food (only 2 of 5 dishes were on the table) and a very rude server named Michaela said in the most condescending, apathetic tone that she had no idea what was going on with our food and that it was "probably coming out." They comped our desserts and hastily gave my brother another drink at the end of the meal and charged us for the rest of our drinks and took off my pasta.  I've never written a restaurant review as I've also worked in the restaurant industry for a number of years but, this experience was truly terrible and stayed with me for days.  I live in the area and my friends were going to eat there after us but, we explained what happened.  They lost over 10 local customers based on the poor service and sadly, the food.

All is well until you slowly pull out a long hair thats been cooked into your lasagna dish. Vomit? Pretty much.  The husband and I came here for what we thought would be a nice, quiet afternoon bite. We were greeted by a friendly employee who told us to sit anywhere we liked and brought us water and menus.  I wasn't very hungry so I was going to order an appetizer and husband ordered a main. I ordered the Asparagi and he, the Lasagna which was per the waiters recommendation. We also ordered a glass of wine and a cocktail.  The restaurant was fairly empty with a couple of other patrons there so it was weird that the drinks took over 5 minutes to come to us but we let it slide. But then when the food took a while to come too it became a little frustrating.  Anyways, food arrives and we begin to eat. The asapargi was OK. It was roasted asparagus with a poached egg, parm and some other blob of something cheesy atop. My husband was really enjoying his lasagna when all of a sudden he digs in and his fork catches a hair that was seriously cooked deep into the dish. I may or may not have gagged but ugh, you know, it's everyones worst nightmare.  We stopped eating and asked for the bill. When the waiter came back to the table we showed him the treasure we found and he was really sorry. He did take the dish off the bill and if it was anything less than a hair I'd give them more stars but I can't get passed that. It is unhygienic on all accounts and I don't know what else goes on in their kitchen.  I will not be returning anytime soon or ever for that matter.

My husband and I had been waiting for Larina to open, walking by every couple days to check on their progress, curious to see what they'd bring to the neighborhood -- and after walking by earlier this afternoon, we'd learn LaRina would be open this evening & made a plan to check it out with a friend.  So glad we did.  Without question, LaRina is my favorite new restaurant in the area -- and among my favorite dining experiences worldwide (seriously folks, it's that good).  To begin, the decor is near perfect...a cozy mix of old & new -- considered, yet unfussy.  Nice enough to feel fancy, casual enough to show up in jeans.  LaRina's menu approaches Italian fare like  Alexander McQueen designed clothing.  As considered as the interiors & branding, Chef Silvia's creative menu avoids cliched, staid dishes (no spaghetti bolognese here) and instead crafts a new Italian -- a sophisticated yet accessible fare cool enough to impress your clients, relatable enough to keep visiting parents happy.  We tried three appetizers (a fresh burrata served with peanuts, a delicious cold beet & fig salad served with prosciutto & selection of fried pickled veggies) and decided to share a sampling of 5 pastas (all made in house) as part of a tasting menu chosen by the chef -- each completely outstanding in their own right -- and incredible paired alongside a house-made focaccia (the best way to scrape all the goodness from the bowls).  We finished it all off with a yogurt cake topped with a house-made fruit relish & fresh cream & an equally delicious biscotti served with a lemon ricotta custard.  Alongside a pitch-perfect atmosphere & top-10 meal came service that was both warm & enthusiastic -- clearly this team is proud -- and they have every right to be.  Their hard work has definitely paid off (and I hope it continues to pay off in spades) as you end up feeling like you've just spent the evening at an established favorite rather than the newcomer it is...making it my new favorite.  Welcome to the neighborhood, LaRina -- we're glad you're here.
